{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= D2 submarine.jpg |Ship caption= HMS D2 }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=United Kingdom |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}} |Ship name=HMS ''D2'' |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= |Ship builder=[[Vickers-Armstrongs|Vickers Armstrong]], [[Barrow-in-Furness]] |Ship laid down=10 July 1909 |Ship launched= |Ship christened= |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned=29 March 1911 |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship renamed= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship fate=Sunk, 25 November 1914 |Ship status= |Ship homeport= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class=[[British D-class submarine|D-class submarine]] |Ship displacement=*{{convert|483|LT|t|abbr=on}} (surfaced) *{{convert|595|LT|t|abbr=on}} (submerged) |Ship length={{convert|163|ft|m|abbr=on}} ([[Length overall|o/a]]) |Ship beam={{convert|13.6|ft|m|abbr=on}} (o/a) |Ship draught= |Ship power=*{{convert|1750|hp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on}} (diesel engines) *{{convert|550|hp|kW|abbr=on}} (electric motors) |Ship propulsion=*2 × [[diesel engine]]s *2 × electric motors *2 × screws |Ship speed='''Surfaced:''' {{convert|14|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}} '''Submerged:''' {{convert|10|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} (design); {{convert|9|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} (service) |Ship range=*{{convert|2500|nmi|mi km|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|10|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} (surfaced) *{{convert|45|nmi|mi km|abbr=on}} at {{convert|5|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} (submerged) |Ship endurance= |Ship test depth= |Ship complement=25 |Ship armament=3 × [[British 18 inch torpedo|18 inch (450 mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s (2 forward, 1 stern) |Ship notes= }} |}
'''HMS ''D2''''' was one of eight [[British D-class submarine|D-class submarine]] built for the [[Royal Navy]] during the first decade of the 20th century.
==Description== The D-class submarines were designed as improved and enlarged versions of the preceding [[British C-class submarine|C class]], with [[diesel engine]]s replacing the dangerous [[petrol engine]]s used earlier. ''D2'' was slightly smaller than her sister ships and had a length of {{convert|162|ft|1|in|m|1}} [[length overall|overall]], a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|20|ft|6|in|m|1}} and a mean [[draft (ship)|draught]] of {{convert|10|ft|10|in|m|1}}. She [[displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|489|LT|t}} on the surface and {{convert|603|LT|t}} submerged.<ref>Harrison, Chapter 4</ref> The D-class submarines had a crew of 25 officers and [[other ranks (UK)|other ranks]] and were the first to adopt [[saddle tank (submarine)|saddle tanks]].<ref name=gg9>Gardiner & Gray, p. 87</ref>
For surface running, the boats were powered by two {{convert|600|bhp|lk=in|0|adj=on}} diesels, each driving one [[propeller shaft]]. When submerged each propeller was driven by a {{convert|275|hp|0|adj=on}} [[electric motor]]. They could reach {{convert|14|kn|lk=in}} on the surface and {{convert|9|kn}} underwater. On the surface, the D class had a range of {{convert|2500|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|10|kn}}.<ref name=gg9/>
The boats were armed with three [[British 18 inch torpedo|18-inch (45&nbsp;cm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s, two in the bow and one in the stern. They carried one reload for each tube, a total of six torpedoes.<ref name=gg9/>
==Construction and career== ''D2'' was [[laid down]] by [[Vickers]] on 10 July 1909 at their [[Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow]] shipyard and commissioned on 29 March 1911. During her career, ''D2'' returned from the second [[Heligoland Bight]] patrol along with {{HMS|D3||2}}, {{HMS|E5||2}} and {{HMS|E7||2}}. On 28 August 1914, ''D2'', ''D3'' and {{HMS|D8||2}} fought in the [[Battle of Heligoland Bight (1914)|Battle of Heligoland Bight]]. Then, two days before ''D2'' met her fate, [[Lieutenant commander|Lieutenant Commander]] Jameson was washed overboard off [[Harwich Dockyard|Harwich]]. Lt. Cdr. Head was his replacement. ''D2'' was rammed and sunk by a German patrol boat off [[Borkum]] on 25 November 1914, leaving no survivors.
